    <blockquote>
      <p>
        For years, natural gas production in the Haynesville Shale in the southern U.S. was too difficult and costly. However, in the mid- to late-2000s, advances in 
        <span class="term " data-term="hydraulic fracturing" title="Click to define" tabindex="0">
          hydraulic fracturing
          <icon class="icon-book"></icon>
        </span>
        and horizontal drilling techniques, as well as rising natural gas prices, made extracting natural gas in the region both technically feasible and profitable for the extractive industries.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <h2 id="geology-and-history">Geology and history</h2>
    <p>The Haynesville sedimentary rock formation rests 10,000 feet to 13,000 feet below the surface of northwestern Louisiana, eastern Texas, and southwestern Arkansas. DeSoto Parish, home to approximately 27,000 people, sits at the center of the Haynesville Shale.<sup id="fnref:1"><a href="#fn:1" class="footnote">1</a></sup> In the early 2000s, DeSoto Parishs economy consisted primarily of cattle and dairy farming, and forest extraction. However, DeSotos economy transformed when the Chesapeake Energy Corporation drilled the first exploratory well in the Haynesville Shale in 2007, setting off a natural gas boom in the parish in 2008.<sup id="fnref:2"><a href="#fn:2" class="footnote">2</a></sup></p>
    <h2 id="production">Production</h2>
    <p>From 2007 to 2011, natural gas production quadrupled in northern Louisiana, where DeSoto Parish is located.<sup id="fnref:3"><a href="#fn:3" class="footnote">3</a></sup> More recently, declining natural gas prices have resulted in lower production numbers. For example, the spot price at the Henry Hub in Louisiana fell by about 6% from 2015 to 2016 (from an average $2.62 per MMBtu to an average of $2.46 per MMBtu in 2016).<sup id="fnref:4"><a href="#fn:4" class="footnote">4</a></sup> Production in the region fell from 2.9 trillion cubic feet in 2012 to 1.67 trillion cubic feet in 2016.<sup id="fnref:5"><a href="#fn:5" class="footnote">5</a></sup></p>
    <p>In 2015, Louisiana had a total of 16 trillion cubic feet of proved natural gas reserves.<sup id="fnref:6"><a href="#fn:6" class="footnote">6</a></sup> Louisiana experienced the largest drop in natural gas production in the country in 2015, with a decline of 8%.<sup id="fnref:7"><a href="#fn:7" class="footnote">7</a></sup></p>
    <p>
      In 2015, the U.S. Energy Information Administration estimated that there were 12.8 trillion cubic feet of 
      <span class="term " data-term="proved reserves" title="Click to define" tabindex="0">
        proved reserves
        <icon class="icon-book"></icon>
      </span>
      in the Haneysville/Bossier Shale in Texas and Louisiana.<sup id="fnref:8"><a href="#fn:8" class="footnote">8</a></sup> Louisiana ranked sixth in the nation for proved shale gas reserves.<sup id="fnref:9"><a href="#fn:9" class="footnote">9</a></sup>
    </p>
    <h3 id="natural-gas-production-in-northern-louisiana">Natural gas production in northern Louisiana<sup id="fnref:10"><a href="#fn:10" class="footnote">10</a></sup></h3>
    <p><img src="/public/img/counties/la-production.svg" alt="Chart shows natural gas production in northern Louisiana from 2007 to 2016 as a line graph. The y-axis represents trillions of cubic feet of natural gas, and tops out at 3 trillion cubic feet. From 2007 to 2009, annual natural gas production rose from about 1.3 to 1.4 trillion cubic feet, then rose to levels of over 2.8 trillion in 2011 and 2012. Since 2012, production declined to its 2016 level of under 1.8 trillion." class="case_studies_content-graph"></p>
    <h2 id="employment">Employment</h2>
    <p>Employment data for the complete oil and gas industry in DeSoto Parish is unavailable.<sup id="fnref:11"><a href="#fn:11" class="footnote">11</a></sup>&nbsp;The data that does exist shows that 304 people, about 1% of DeSotos 26,965 residents, work in support activities for oil and gas extraction.<sup id="fnref:12"><a href="#fn:12" class="footnote">12</a></sup> That figure does not include those working directly in oil and gas extraction itself. Data also exists for employment in the broader extractive industries  which includes oil and gas extraction, but also mining and quarrying. The chart below shows the increase in employment in the broader extractive industries in DeSoto Parish between 2006 and 2015.<sup id="fnref:13"><a href="#fn:13" class="footnote">13</a></sup></p>
    <h3 id="wage-and-salary-employment-in-desoto-parish-extractive-industries-vs-all-other-industries">Wage and salary employment in DeSoto Parish: Extractive industries vs. all other industries<sup id="fnref:14"><a href="#fn:14" class="footnote">14</a></sup></h3>
    <p><img src="/public/img/counties/la-wage.svg" alt="Chart shows the number of jobs in DeSoto Parish from 2007 to 2016. The y-axis, which represents the number of wage and salary employees, tops out at 7,000, and each bar compares the number of extractive industry jobs to the total number of jobs that year. Each bar also identifies the percentage of jobs in the extractive industries. The total number of jobs each year ranges from about 4,100 to a little under 6,000. The percentage of jobs in the extractive industries is between 8% (in 2007 and 2008) and 21% (in 2012). Since 2013, mining, quarrying, and oil and gas jobs have represented between 17% and 18% of DeSoto Parish jobs." class="case_studies_content-graph"></p>
    <h2 id="revenue">Revenue</h2>
    <p>The Haynesville Shale natural gas boom has increased revenue for the State of Louisiana and DeSoto Parish through state severance taxes and royalties, parish property taxes, and sales and use taxes.</p>
    <p>
      The state of Louisiana levies a severance tax on natural gas owners at a rate of $0.111 per 
      <span class="term " data-term="Mcf" title="Click to define" tabindex="0">
        Mcf
        <icon class="icon-book"></icon>
      </span>
      produced.<sup id="fnref:15"><a href="#fn:15" class="footnote">15</a></sup> In 2015, Louisiana received $190 million from gas severance taxes across the state, up from $148 million in 2014.<sup id="fnref:16"><a href="#fn:16" class="footnote">16</a></sup> Through the end of November 2016, however, the state had only received $119 million.<sup id="fnref:16:1"><a href="#fn:16" class="footnote">16</a></sup> It also received $61.8 million from gas royalties for production on state-owned lands and water bottoms in 2016, down from $85.6 million in 2015 and $166.8 million in 2014.<sup id="fnref:18"><a href="#fn:18" class="footnote">17</a></sup> The state distributes some of this revenue to the parishes where extraction took place. For severance taxes, one-fifth of taxes return to the parish, as long as the total does not exceed $750,000.<sup id="fnref:19"><a href="#fn:19" class="footnote">18</a></sup> For royalties, 10% return to the parish.<sup id="fnref:20"><a href="#fn:20" class="footnote">19</a></sup> Royalties are bid on for each lease, and by law they cannot be less than 1/8 of the value of production.<sup id="fnref:21"><a href="#fn:21" class="footnote">20</a></sup> In 2014, for example, DeSoto Parish received $624,592 in royalties, rents, and bonuses  which accounted for 2% of DeSoto Parishs total revenue. (Taxes made up 69% of parish revenue.)<sup id="fnref:22"><a href="#fn:22" class="footnote">21</a></sup> Louisiana also collects 1% of gross receipts from the operation of natural gas franchises or charters in the state.<sup id="fnref:23"><a href="#fn:23" class="footnote">22</a></sup>
    </p>
    <p>In addition to the state, DeSoto Parish also collects revenue from natural gas production, most notably in the form of property taxes. Revenue from property taxes increases with the assessed value of the property, and is the largest source of revenue for DeSoto Parish.  According to the parish school board, the discovery of shale gas increased property values in Desoto Parish starting in 2008. From fiscal year 2009 to 2015, the taxable value of property within the parish increased by 160%, or from $292 million to $750 million.<sup id="fnref:24"><a href="#fn:24" class="footnote">23</a></sup> <sup id="fnref:25"><a href="#fn:25" class="footnote">24</a></sup> <sup id="fnref:26"><a href="#fn:26" class="footnote">25</a></sup> However, information from the DeSoto Parish Tax Assessor shows parishwide taxable property values decreased in fiscal year 2016 to approximately $687 million, <sup id="fnref:27"><a href="#fn:27" class="footnote">26</a></sup> In 2016, property taxes exceeded $40 million.<sup id="fnref:28"><a href="#fn:28" class="footnote">27</a></sup> Property tax revenues are used for numerous purposes, including to pay off long-term debt which was sold to build new schools.<sup id="fnref:29"><a href="#fn:29" class="footnote">28</a></sup></p>
    <p>Sales and use taxes are the second largest source of revenue for DeSoto Parish. Natural gas exploration and development spurred greater revenue from sales and use taxes, which increased from $8 million in fiscal year 2005 to $73 million in fiscal year 2011. This trend has since reversed, and sales and use tax accounted for $18 million in revenue in fiscal year 2015.<sup id="fnref:30"><a href="#fn:30" class="footnote">29</a></sup></p>
    <p>Sales and use taxes are deposited into the General Fund, School Lunch Fund, Debt Service Fund, and Capital Projects Fund.<sup id="fnref:31"><a href="#fn:31" class="footnote">30</a></sup> While sales and use taxes are not solely attributable to the natural gas industry, there is a noticeable decline in this revenue stream when the industry faces slowdowns. For example, sales and use taxes declined by $27 million (40%) in 2013 compared to the prior fiscal year, as exploration for oil and natural gas moved to other parts of the country.<sup id="fnref:32"><a href="#fn:32" class="footnote">31</a></sup></p>
    <h3 id="sales-and-use-taxes-">Sales and use taxes <sup id="fnref:33"><a href="#fn:33" class="footnote">32</a></sup></h3>
    <p><img src="/public/img/counties/la-tax.svg" alt="Chart shows sales and use tax trends in DeSoto Parish as a bar graph. The y-axis represents millions of dollars and tops out at $80 million. Sales and use taxes in the parish range from around $10 million in 2006 to over $70 million in 2011. In 2012, tax revenue dropped to under $50 million, then just under $20 million by 2015." class="case_studies_content-graph"></p>
    <p>Property taxes also contribute substantially to the school boards revenue, funding employee salaries, operations, and debt service payments on capital bonds for the local education system.<sup id="fnref:34"><a href="#fn:34" class="footnote">33</a></sup> The amount of revenue from property taxes increased by 52% from 2012 ($26.5 million) to 2016 ($40.2 million).<sup id="fnref:35"><a href="#fn:35" class="footnote">34</a></sup> State tax documents do not specify what percentage of property taxes comes from the gas industry.</p>
    <h2 id="costs">Costs</h2>
    <p>Since 2008, Louisiana has invested at least $1.1 billion in transportation projects in the seven parishes located in the northwest region of the state, including DeSoto Parish.<sup id="fnref:34:1"><a href="#fn:34" class="footnote">33</a></sup> While Louisianas latest comprehensive state transportation plan acknowledges that the state must pay adequate attention to the transportation needs of the rapidly expanding oil and gas industry, it does not specify the types or costs of projects supported.<sup id="fnref:36"><a href="#fn:36" class="footnote">35</a></sup></p>
    <p>Louisiana completed a <a href="http://dnr.louisiana.gov/assets/OC/haynesville_shale/071311_stronger_review.pdf">Hydraulic Fracturing State Review (PDF)</a> in March 2011, which explains the states policies around industrial water use and wastewater reuse and disposal. However, the review does not itemize public expenditures on water-related infrastructure for industrial activities.<sup id="fnref:37"><a href="#fn:37" class="footnote">36</a></sup></p>
    <p>
      The DeSoto Parish Emergency Medical Services (EMS) Department formed in 2001, funded by a 4% 
      <span class="term term-end" data-term="millage tax" title="Click to define" tabindex="0">
        millage tax
        <icon class="icon-book"></icon>
      </span>
      .<sup id="fnref:38"><a href="#fn:38" class="footnote">37</a></sup> Since then, the DeSoto EMS Department has worked closely with gas companies on safety measures, including answering numerous calls related to gas-well site incidents. The parish is not bearing the full burden of these incidents; the parish has received donations from private companies to offset equipment costs. The frequency and value of the donations is not published.
    </p>

            <span class="term " data-term="north american industry classification system (naics)" title="Click to define" tabindex="0">
              NAICS
              <icon class="icon-book"></icon>
            </span>
            code: 21) for the parish. For any employment estimates identified using the letter-coded ranges (e.g., a = 019 employees), the average number was used (e.g., a = 9.5 employees).
          </td>

          <p>Louisiana Department of Transportation and Development, <a href="http://wwwsp.dotd.la.gov/Inside_LaDOTD/Divisions/Administration/Documents/DOTD%20Accomplishments_cover.swf">Accomplishments 20082014 (SWF)</a>, p. 18&nbsp;<a href="#fnref:36" class="reversefootnote"></a></p>
        </li>
        <li id="fn:37">
          <p><a href="http://wwwsp.dotd.la.gov/Inside_LaDOTD/Divisions/Multimodal/Transportation_Plan/2003%20Statewide%20Transportation%20Plan/10%20Chapter%207%20-%20Transportation%20Plan%20Development.pdf">Louisiana Statewide Transportation Plan, Chapter 7: Transportation Plan Development (PDF)</a>, 2003, p. 7-50&nbsp;<a href="#fnref:37" class="reversefootnote"></a></p>
        </li>
        <li id="fn:38">
          <p>Louisiana Department of Natural Resources, <a href="http://dnr.louisiana.gov/assets/OC/haynesville_shale/071311_stronger_review.pdf">Louisiana Hydraulic Fracturing State Review (PDF)</a>, 2011, p. 16&nbsp;<a href="#fnref:38" class="reversefootnote"></a></p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
